Yes—if you don’t store the theme anywhere, it will reset to the default each time the page reloads. The simplest way to make the choice persist is to write it to `localStorage` (or a cookie) when the user selects a theme, and then read that value on page load to re‑apply the same CSS class or stylesheet.

**Example using localStorage**

```html
<!-- Theme toggle button -->
<button id="themeToggle">Toggle Dark/Light</button>

<script>
// Apply saved theme on page load
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const saved = localStorage.getItem('theme'); // "dark" or "light"
  if (saved) {
    document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', saved);
  }
});

// Toggle theme and store the choice
document.getElementById('themeToggle').addEventListener('click', () => {
  const current = document.documentElement.getAttribute('data-theme') === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark';
  document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', current);
  localStorage.setItem('theme', current);
});
</script>

<style>
/* Light theme (default) */
:root[data-theme="light"] {
  --bg: #fff;
  --text: #000;
}

/* Dark theme */
:root[data-theme="dark"] {
  --bg: #111;
  --text: #eee;
}

body {
  background: var(--bg);
  color: var(--text);
}
</style>
```

**Key points**

1. **Write the choice** – `localStorage.setItem('theme', value)` stores the string permanently (until the user clears it).
2. **Read on load** – When the page loads, retrieve the value with `localStorage.getItem('theme')` and set the appropriate class or data attribute.
3. **Fallback** – If nothing is stored, you can default to the system preference (`window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)')`) or a default theme.
4. **Cookies** – If you need the theme to be sent to the server (e.g., for server‑side rendering), set a cookie instead of localStorage; the logic is similar.

Using this approach, the user’s theme selection survives page reloads, navigation, and even browser restarts, as long as the storage isn’t cleared.

