Debounce waits until the user stops generating events, so it’s great for things like a search box where you only want to act after the typing pauses. For continuous movement such as scrolling, you usually want regular updates while the motion is happening, which makes throttling the better choice. A throttled handler guarantees that you get a callback at a predictable interval (e.g., every 16 ms) regardless of how many scroll events fire, keeping the UI responsive. In practice, many developers combine a throttle with `requestAnimationFrame` so the visual work runs in sync with the browser’s paint cycle:

```js
let ticking = false;

function onScroll() {
  if (!ticking) {
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      // perform UI updates here (e.g., lazy‑load images, update scroll position)
      ticking = false;
    });
    ticking = true;
  }
}

// Throttle the scroll listener to ~60 fps (≈16 ms)
window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll);
```

This pattern limits the work to once per frame while still reacting to every scroll movement, which is generally smoother than a pure debounce that would only fire after scrolling stops.

